WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:03.879 --> 00:00:05.339
Hey. this is Peter Gould.

2
00:00:05.506 --> 00:00:09.426
This is episode 309. "Fall."

3
00:00:09.593 --> 00:00:12.513
And I'm Gordon Smith.
I wrote this episode.

4
00:00:12.679 --> 00:00:14.640
Minkie Spiro. the director.

5
00:00:14.806 --> 00:00:16.308
Rhea Seehorn. I acted in it.

6
00:00:16.475 --> 00:00:19.770
Bob Odenkirk. I played Jimmy McGill.

7
00:00:19.937 --> 00:00:22.856
Melissa Bernstein.
one of your producers.

8
00:00:23.023 --> 00:00:27.486
Such a funny thing that he bought
the shitty cookies and baked...

9
00:00:27.653 --> 00:00:30.822
-And is passing them off as his own.
-You eat many of your props...

10
00:00:30.989 --> 00:00:33.801
-...in our scenes. Did you eat these?
-I didn't eat those. No. They were just...

11
00:00:33.825 --> 00:00:37.579
-...way too pre-made for me.
-Fattening.

12
00:00:37.746 --> 00:00:41.708
-Well. I think those were...
-Those are for your bomb shelter.

13
00:00:42.459 --> 00:00:44.211
Those are bomb shelter cookies.

14
00:00:44.378 --> 00:00:47.965
Thirty years later you're like.
"I'm so glad I packed these away."

15
00:00:48.131 --> 00:00:51.093
I thought those were gluten-free.
I'm surprised.

16
00:00:51.260 --> 00:00:52.886
-There's Irene.
-Here we are...

17
00:00:53.053 --> 00:00:55.472
-...back at Sandpiper Crossing.
-That is a fine...

18
00:00:55.639 --> 00:00:58.308
...wonderful actress named Jean Effron.

19
00:00:59.142 --> 00:01:00.978
She is great.

20
00:01:01.812 --> 00:01:04.815
-Kiira Arai found her last season.
-Isn't she?

21
00:01:04.982 --> 00:01:07.818
-No. it was the season before last.
-Season one. season one.

22
00:01:07.985 --> 00:01:10.070
-Is she local to New Mexico. then?
-She is.

23
00:01:10.237 --> 00:01:12.573
-She is.
-Initially. she was just somebody...

24
00:01:12.739 --> 00:01:15.784
...to say "Bingo." in Genny's episode.

25
00:01:15.951 --> 00:01:18.912
And we liked her so much
that when we had the plot line...

26
00:01:19.079 --> 00:01:21.373
...about finding one of his clients...

27
00:01:21.540 --> 00:01:22.892
...finding something
at Sandpiper Crossing...

28
00:01:22.916 --> 00:01:25.127
...we're like. "She was great.
What if we did her?"

29
00:01:25.294 --> 00:01:26.503
-That's great.
-My God.

30
00:01:26.670 --> 00:01:29.256
And she was doing a play
after this season.

31
00:01:29.423 --> 00:01:32.634
I don't know what it was.
but she's... She is an actress.

32
00:01:32.801 --> 00:01:35.971
It's not one of those things
where she's never done it.

33
00:01:36.138 --> 00:01:38.849
But there was this anxiety.
could she hold this story line?

34
00:01:39.016 --> 00:01:41.602
But she was...
She absolutely stepped up.

35
00:01:41.768 --> 00:01:42.811
-Amazing.
-Yeah.

36
00:01:44.229 --> 00:01:47.608
And this is...
She has so much to do in this episode.

37
00:01:47.774 --> 00:01:49.359
She's wonderful.

38
00:01:49.526 --> 00:01:52.070
And I love the way
you play this one. Bob.

39
00:01:52.237 --> 00:01:54.156
Because Jimmy...

40
00:01:55.449 --> 00:01:58.052
-...he hasn't quite made the decision...
-This is the giveaway. right here.

41
00:01:58.076 --> 00:01:59.703
...to go as dark as he goes.

42
00:01:59.870 --> 00:02:02.289
-Yeah.
-But he thinks maybe this will be easy.

43
00:02:02.456 --> 00:02:04.625
And... But he's got a hidden agenda here.

44
00:02:04.791 --> 00:02:07.210
-Yeah.
-Not very well-hidden.

45
00:02:07.377 --> 00:02:10.172
Yeah. but she sure can't see it.

46
00:02:10.339 --> 00:02:13.467
I appreciate that this shot
includes the fantastic set dec...

47
00:02:13.634 --> 00:02:16.178
-...of the painting in the background.
-So great.

48
00:02:16.345 --> 00:02:19.848
Who doesn't want
one cinder block wall in their house?

49
00:02:21.391 --> 00:02:23.393
I mean. these legal notices...

50
00:02:23.560 --> 00:02:26.021
So. Minkie. you...

51
00:02:26.188 --> 00:02:27.814
You're not from here.

52
00:02:27.981 --> 00:02:29.566
Funny you should say that.

53
00:02:29.733 --> 00:02:33.028
-You're not from Albuquerque.
-No.

54
00:02:33.195 --> 00:02:34.237
Where are you from?

55
00:02:34.404 --> 00:02:36.114
Where have you done
most of your directing?

56
00:02:36.281 --> 00:02:39.076
I'm based in London.
born and brought up there.

57
00:02:39.242 --> 00:02:43.330
And I was very chuffed when Melissa
and your fine self-invited me...

58
00:02:43.497 --> 00:02:46.875
-...to come and take part in the show.
-That means insulted.

59
00:02:47.376 --> 00:02:49.836
Or infuriated. I thought.

60
00:02:50.337 --> 00:02:51.797
But...

61
00:02:52.964 --> 00:02:57.010
Minkie is probably...
You should IMDb her.

62
00:02:57.177 --> 00:03:00.514
She has done some amazing work.

63
00:03:00.681 --> 00:03:04.184
She's having quite an incredible career.
and we were so lucky...

64
00:03:04.351 --> 00:03:08.397
...to get her for this
very pivotal episode.

65
00:03:08.563 --> 00:03:11.024
And it's always...

66
00:03:11.191 --> 00:03:13.694
I will admit
that it's always a little nail-biting...

67
00:03:13.860 --> 00:03:18.365
...to bring in a new director.
and you just never quite know.

68
00:03:18.532 --> 00:03:22.160
And just...
Minkie just hit this out of the park.

69
00:03:22.327 --> 00:03:26.456
And I was just so. so happy
with the way this one came out.

70
00:03:26.623 --> 00:03:29.793
I love your American expressions.
"Hit it out of the park."

71
00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:31.521
I remember
when somebody first said that to me.

72
00:03:31.545 --> 00:03:33.463
I had no idea
what you were talking about.

73
00:03:33.630 --> 00:03:36.675
I had to get a translation.
Which it's to do with baseball. right?

74
00:03:36.842 --> 00:03:38.282
-I guess.
-Once you figured it out...

75
00:03:38.343 --> 00:03:41.221
...you were chuffed. so...
You were quite chuffed about it.

76
00:03:41.388 --> 00:03:42.889
Good. good. good.

77
00:03:43.056 --> 00:03:45.851
This was a complicated episode too.
because we...

78
00:03:46.017 --> 00:03:49.020
I don't think we really realized
how difficult it was gonna be...

79
00:03:49.187 --> 00:03:50.748
...when we were breaking it in the room.

80
00:03:50.772 --> 00:03:53.275
Because there's just
so many moving parts and we had...

81
00:03:53.442 --> 00:03:56.278
...extras and we had a very large cast...

82
00:03:56.445 --> 00:03:59.406
...a lot of scenes and a ton of locations.
This is a practical location.

83
00:03:59.573 --> 00:04:02.075
So we were running around from...

84
00:04:02.242 --> 00:04:04.453
...dawn until... Till midday.

85
00:04:04.828 --> 00:04:07.789
Sometimes not taking lunch
for 10 hours at a stretch...

86
00:04:07.956 --> 00:04:09.958
...just because
we were fighting daylight.

87
00:04:10.125 --> 00:04:13.044
This is shot in the middle of January...

88
00:04:13.211 --> 00:04:15.255
...so we had very little daylight...

89
00:04:15.422 --> 00:04:17.716
-...but there was a lot of exteriors.
-Yeah.

90
00:04:17.883 --> 00:04:21.720
And having to work in a working mall.
where we were only allowed there...

91
00:04:21.887 --> 00:04:22.929
...before it opened.

92
00:04:23.096 --> 00:04:26.099
There were just a number
of small challenges that added up...

93
00:04:26.266 --> 00:04:30.312
...to it being a really challenging shoot
to kind of keep everyone together.

94
00:04:30.479 --> 00:04:32.272
These ladies are amazing.

95
00:04:32.439 --> 00:04:36.485
Bonnie Bartlett is the actress
on the right there that you saw.

96
00:04:36.985 --> 00:04:39.780
Of <i>St Elsewhere.</i>
among many other things.

97
00:04:39.946 --> 00:04:42.199
-And <i>Little House on the Prairie.</i> I think.
-Yeah.

98
00:04:42.365 --> 00:04:43.867
Yeah.

99
00:04:45.118 --> 00:04:50.040
Those three. Phyllis. Bonnie and Carol.
are just wonderful.

100
00:04:50.207 --> 00:04:54.586
They...
They're just so beautifully orchestrated.

101
00:04:54.753 --> 00:04:57.506
They have three...
It's also three wonderful voices.

102
00:04:57.672 --> 00:04:59.591
-Each one of them has a different...
-Yeah.

103
00:04:59.758 --> 00:05:01.802
Is in a different pitch.
a different octave.

104
00:05:01.968 --> 00:05:04.554
And they're just fun to listen to.
They're fun to watch.

105
00:05:04.721 --> 00:05:06.932
And they just... They just brought it.

106
00:05:07.098 --> 00:05:09.434
And you believe you've fallen
into a sewing circle.

107
00:05:09.601 --> 00:05:13.480
Like they... They go way back
and have a shorthand.

108
00:05:13.647 --> 00:05:15.357
And they had never met before.

109
00:05:15.524 --> 00:05:16.817
-Really?
-I don't think so.

110
00:05:16.983 --> 00:05:20.487
They met on the airplane.
flying over from L.A.

111
00:05:20.904 --> 00:05:23.323
Oh. Saul. Getting peed on.

112
00:05:23.490 --> 00:05:24.866
Smells so good.

113
00:05:25.033 --> 00:05:26.993
You're in trouble.

114
00:05:29.287 --> 00:05:34.042
The titles. of course. change
each season a little bit. very subtly.

115
00:05:34.209 --> 00:05:36.795
Sad as can be. but...

116
00:05:38.797 --> 00:05:40.173
Where is Mike?

117
00:05:40.340 --> 00:05:44.302
-Where could he possibly be?
-What is happening?

118
00:05:44.469 --> 00:05:45.720
What?

119
00:05:45.887 --> 00:05:48.515
One of my favorite moments. there.

120
00:05:49.432 --> 00:05:51.685
Did you have to hire someone
who had special skills...

121
00:05:51.852 --> 00:05:53.538
...at the bottom that says.
"Rides a Segway"?

122
00:05:53.562 --> 00:05:55.730
-Yes.
-He... The guy came with the Segway.

123
00:05:55.897 --> 00:05:57.190
-Stop it.
-It was his Segway.

124
00:05:57.357 --> 00:05:59.985
-Damn it. I need to do my special skills.
-He did that.

125
00:06:00.151 --> 00:06:03.530
And this is shot in a building
right next to our studio.

126
00:06:03.697 --> 00:06:06.491
-But where they're walking into...
-And now it's a different building.

127
00:06:06.658 --> 00:06:07.701
-Yes.
-Oh. it is?

128
00:06:07.868 --> 00:06:09.035
-Yes.
-I wasn't there.

129
00:06:09.202 --> 00:06:13.248
This is another location
that we shot back in <i>Breaking Bad.</i>

130
00:06:14.082 --> 00:06:16.376
-Same office.
-There she is.

131
00:06:16.543 --> 00:06:18.712
I love Laura Fraser.
I didn't get to meet her.

132
00:06:18.879 --> 00:06:21.548
Laura Fraser. who's just wonderful.

133
00:06:21.715 --> 00:06:26.261
And it's interesting. we really felt
that that waiting room scene...

134
00:06:26.428 --> 00:06:30.682
...had value to bring Mike
into this new world.

135
00:06:30.849 --> 00:06:33.768
But it was a pain in the neck to shoot.
because it was. like...

136
00:06:33.935 --> 00:06:36.104
-Why?
-Because it was a different location.

137
00:06:36.271 --> 00:06:40.066
Because this office building
doesn't have a useable lobby...

138
00:06:40.233 --> 00:06:42.944
...not a lobby that size.
So we had to dress...

139
00:06:43.111 --> 00:06:44.404
-This building's tiny.
-Yeah.

140
00:06:44.571 --> 00:06:46.197
-Yes.
-Tiny. little office.

141
00:06:46.364 --> 00:06:49.367
Why the decision
to have a Degas sculpture?

142
00:06:49.784 --> 00:06:51.828
I think that was originally
in <i>Breaking Bad.</i>

143
00:06:51.995 --> 00:06:53.997
It was. I think it was...
I think it was Sam.

144
00:06:54.164 --> 00:06:57.375
I think Sam Catlin... I think it was
his episode and he thought that...

145
00:06:57.542 --> 00:06:59.836
...that was something that felt like...

146
00:07:00.003 --> 00:07:02.505
...the way that Lydia
would conceive of herself...

147
00:07:02.672 --> 00:07:04.942
-...in terms of the ballerina of it.
-That's why I was wondering.

148
00:07:04.966 --> 00:07:06.611
It's such a modern office
and then there's that.

149
00:07:06.635 --> 00:07:08.511
-Yes. yeah.
-Interesting.

150
00:07:08.678 --> 00:07:13.516
I've had people talk to me
who assumed it was <i>Fearless Girl.</i>

151
00:07:13.683 --> 00:07:16.811
-Oh. interesting. On Wall Street now.
-Which is part of the...

152
00:07:16.978 --> 00:07:20.231
Part of the Wall Street statue war.

153
00:07:20.815 --> 00:07:21.858
Oh. right.

154
00:07:22.025 --> 00:07:24.569
Laura Fraser.
also not from here. like Minkie.

155
00:07:24.736 --> 00:07:27.739
-Scottish.
-Scottish. Lovely Scottish actress.

156
00:07:29.074 --> 00:07:32.661
This is also... In sort of the story terms.
this is the first meeting...

157
00:07:32.827 --> 00:07:34.955
...that Mike and Lydia have.

158
00:07:35.121 --> 00:07:39.751
Which. of course.
we see them much later in their lives.

159
00:07:39.918 --> 00:07:41.711
In a much different place...

160
00:07:41.878 --> 00:07:45.674
...kind of worrying
about the demise of Gus Fring.

161
00:07:45.840 --> 00:07:48.718
But this is their introduction.

162
00:07:48.885 --> 00:07:52.764
I love the way Laura plays it
because she was cast originally...

163
00:07:52.931 --> 00:07:56.267
...to be Lydia on <i>Breaking Bad.</i>
whose hair is on fire.

164
00:07:56.434 --> 00:08:02.607
She's in an extreme state of anxiety
from the first moment that we see her.

165
00:08:03.108 --> 00:08:05.360
And now we get to see Lydia...

166
00:08:05.527 --> 00:08:09.698
A calmer Lydia. but she still seems...

167
00:08:09.864 --> 00:08:11.741
...brittle. might be a word I'd use.

168
00:08:11.908 --> 00:08:14.953
She seems... She's still Lydia.

169
00:08:15.120 --> 00:08:18.623
And I don't... Laura has just
such an interesting way...

170
00:08:18.790 --> 00:08:21.501
...about her
when she gets into this character.

171
00:08:21.668 --> 00:08:24.671
It's a little bit of a crime
that we can't use her real accent...

172
00:08:24.838 --> 00:08:28.758
...because she has
a wonderful Scottish lilt.

173
00:08:28.925 --> 00:08:32.220
And she is. by the way.
if you IMDb her...

174
00:08:32.387 --> 00:08:35.515
If you're... She's on a British show...

175
00:08:35.682 --> 00:08:39.060
...which is. I believe.
about crimes at Loch Ness.

176
00:08:39.227 --> 00:08:40.895
And it sounds terrific.

177
00:08:41.062 --> 00:08:44.024
I've heard wonderful things.
I really wanna watch that.

178
00:08:44.190 --> 00:08:46.860
Is the...? ls the end...?
It's always like. "I don't know...

179
00:08:47.027 --> 00:08:49.195
...these flipper prints
lead back to the ocean.

180
00:08:49.362 --> 00:08:50.697
I don't know who did it."

181
00:08:50.864 --> 00:08:52.574
-It could be.
-Yes. Gordon.

182
00:08:52.741 --> 00:08:55.535
-That is the end of every episode.
-That's why it's so good.

183
00:08:55.702 --> 00:08:58.246
-Yes.
-It could be.

184
00:08:58.788 --> 00:09:01.583
And she's also...
Lydia is styled a bit differently.

185
00:09:01.750 --> 00:09:03.960
Her hair is down.

186
00:09:06.087 --> 00:09:07.672
Uptight.

187
00:09:07.839 --> 00:09:09.883
Yeah. she even gives Mike
a little shit here...

188
00:09:10.050 --> 00:09:12.761
...about working at SMQ Parking.
which is not something...

189
00:09:12.927 --> 00:09:17.057
...that future Lydia.
with her hair on fire. would really do.

190
00:09:17.849 --> 00:09:19.392
Justin?

191
00:09:22.687 --> 00:09:25.374
We had a nightmare with the door. here.
Do you remember. it wouldn't close?

192
00:09:25.398 --> 00:09:26.983
-Yes.
-We had to keep...

193
00:09:27.150 --> 00:09:29.069
-Really?
-Yeah. That door wasn't really...

194
00:09:29.235 --> 00:09:31.279
...intended to be an entry and exit door...

195
00:09:31.446 --> 00:09:34.991
...so we had to kind of figure out
what to do with it to make it work.

196
00:09:35.158 --> 00:09:37.660
So you've got actors laying
on the ground. holding it?

197
00:09:37.827 --> 00:09:40.038
-Pretty much.
-Basically. basically. yeah.

198
00:09:40.205 --> 00:09:42.373
-With a key they have in the door.
-Movie magic.

199
00:09:42.540 --> 00:09:43.917
Yeah.

200
00:09:44.084 --> 00:09:48.463
But. like. normally that door.
in terms of this office's normal use...

201
00:09:48.630 --> 00:09:50.048
...they just lock that door.

202
00:09:50.215 --> 00:09:52.675
So there's not like a...
A latch that closes.

203
00:09:52.842 --> 00:09:54.779
-You have to lock and unlock it.
-I like that she has a key. though.

204
00:09:54.803 --> 00:09:56.429
-Yeah.
-It's like she's like. "No..."

205
00:09:56.596 --> 00:09:58.723
...if you're coming in.
you have to unlock it.

206
00:09:58.890 --> 00:10:02.727
-And you lock every time you leave."
-Yeah. she's in a vault.

207
00:10:02.894 --> 00:10:05.605
-You put a good spin on that.
-Yeah. no. it really feels...

208
00:10:05.772 --> 00:10:07.816
-...like a <i>Breaking Bad...</i>
-A choice.

209
00:10:07.982 --> 00:10:10.944
<i>...Better Call Saul</i> choice.
Like. she has a special office.

210
00:10:11.111 --> 00:10:13.696
Note. it's from producers.

211
00:10:13.863 --> 00:10:16.616
"The key is always in the lock.

212
00:10:17.784 --> 00:10:22.080
Please have discussion.
half an hour at minimum."

213
00:10:22.413 --> 00:10:24.666
Oh. I love this scene.

214
00:10:26.459 --> 00:10:28.503
-And again. it...
-Yeah. it's a great scene...

215
00:10:28.670 --> 00:10:31.714
...where these guys diverge.

216
00:10:32.048 --> 00:10:34.384
Yeah. you see Howard...
Howard's really having...

217
00:10:34.551 --> 00:10:38.429
He's really getting fed up
with Chuck a little bit here.

218
00:10:38.596 --> 00:10:40.807
-Or he's concerned about him anyway.
-Yeah.

219
00:10:40.974 --> 00:10:42.642
And...

220
00:10:42.809 --> 00:10:47.564
They're still on the same side.
at least as far as we can tell right now.

221
00:10:49.232 --> 00:10:52.569
And this is one of the few times
we get to see Chuck kind of...

222
00:10:52.735 --> 00:10:57.240
...not seemingly. at this moment.
hurting from the electricity at HHM.

223
00:10:57.407 --> 00:11:00.618
He's there and he seems pretty...

224
00:11:00.785 --> 00:11:02.545
He's annoyed
with why he's being called in...

225
00:11:02.579 --> 00:11:05.999
...but not hurting from that. notably.

226
00:11:06.166 --> 00:11:08.585
He's putting on a show of a normal guy.

227
00:11:08.751 --> 00:11:13.173
In a moment. the table lamps
are gonna be switched off.

228
00:11:13.339 --> 00:11:15.425
-I seem to remember there was a...
-Oh. my God.

229
00:11:15.592 --> 00:11:18.219
-Was there a problem with that?
-Just a little.

230
00:11:18.386 --> 00:11:20.388
Oddly enough. it was very difficult.

231
00:11:20.555 --> 00:11:24.392
I mean. we were trying to get
the electricians to rewire them.

232
00:11:24.559 --> 00:11:28.771
We tried to find a similar contraption
that we could isolate...

233
00:11:28.938 --> 00:11:30.773
...because they were all on one...

234
00:11:30.940 --> 00:11:32.376
-You couldn't take one out. yeah.
-Circuit?

235
00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:33.735
Yeah.

236
00:11:34.235 --> 00:11:36.237
But luckily.
they did figure out a solution.

237
00:11:36.404 --> 00:11:39.908
This is how Chuck goes through life.
He's just gonna sue you.

238
00:11:40.325 --> 00:11:42.785
-Yeah.
-Who else is like that?

239
00:11:42.952 --> 00:11:44.954
Who in the real world is like that?

240
00:11:45.121 --> 00:11:46.915
-All other lawyers.
-A lot of America.

241
00:11:47.081 --> 00:11:48.333
Not our president.

242
00:11:48.499 --> 00:11:49.918
Oh. wait.

243
00:11:51.461 --> 00:11:54.005
You know. to a hammer.
everything looks like a nail.

244
00:11:54.172 --> 00:11:57.217
I love the tilt back of the chairs
and the shape it makes.

245
00:11:57.383 --> 00:11:59.844
-Well done. The lights went out.
-Yeah.

246
00:12:00.470 --> 00:12:02.388
We managed it.

247
00:12:02.555 --> 00:12:05.516
It's funny. the things...
The things you get hung up on.

248
00:12:05.683 --> 00:12:07.769
And where is the booze
gonna be in this room?

249
00:12:07.936 --> 00:12:09.729
We had to figure out where the booze...

250
00:12:09.896 --> 00:12:12.523
...came from
because we've never seen it before.

251
00:12:12.690 --> 00:12:14.901
A place that would accommodate that.

252
00:12:15.068 --> 00:12:18.655
At this point. I think people should fear
when Hamlin brings out booze.

253
00:12:18.821 --> 00:12:22.158
It doesn't ever seem to be good things
he's gonna say to you.

254
00:12:23.576 --> 00:12:25.787
-"Have some bourbon."
-"Have some bourbon."

255
00:12:25.954 --> 00:12:30.291
"Totally not the poisoned bourbon
this time. promise."

256
00:12:32.043 --> 00:12:35.546
You know. Hamlin. I think.
is giving some pretty good advice here.

257
00:12:35.713 --> 00:12:36.756
Absolutely.

258
00:12:36.923 --> 00:12:39.318
One hundred percent.
this would've been a better out for him.

259
00:12:39.342 --> 00:12:42.095
-Fabian is so great in this season.
-Yeah.

260
00:12:42.262 --> 00:12:46.099
You guys gave him more going on.
and he gets angry...

261
00:12:46.266 --> 00:12:50.436
-...and intense. and he's powerful.
-Yep.

262
00:12:50.603 --> 00:12:53.648
I loved seeing what has been
simmering under Hamlin...

263
00:12:53.815 --> 00:12:56.484
...for three seasons
come out this season.

264
00:12:57.026 --> 00:13:02.282
He's under a lot of pressure. And...
Yeah. Patrick is such a wonderful actor.

265
00:13:02.448 --> 00:13:04.742
-Yeah. and a wonderful person.
-Yeah.

266
00:13:04.909 --> 00:13:07.578
-He's not... I don't feel like...
-He's so-so as a person.

267
00:13:08.079 --> 00:13:10.540
Yeah. but you know what
I think he doesn't get...

268
00:13:10.707 --> 00:13:13.793
...because he's kind of
handsome-y and...

269
00:13:13.960 --> 00:13:15.128
Handsome-y?

270
00:13:15.295 --> 00:13:18.506
You know. he probably doesn't get
what you guys are giving him here...

271
00:13:18.881 --> 00:13:21.721
...which is where he gets to get
really riled up and lay down the law...

272
00:13:21.801 --> 00:13:23.481
You think in other parts
he doesn't get it.

273
00:13:23.511 --> 00:13:25.555
And switch from one... Look.

274
00:13:25.722 --> 00:13:28.057
Maybe it's time to sit down.

275
00:13:28.224 --> 00:13:30.893
-I think you're right.
-Like. that little shit. that kind of stuff.

276
00:13:31.060 --> 00:13:33.521
I just feel so sorry for him
for being so handsome.

277
00:13:33.688 --> 00:13:35.648
-Do you? Do you?
-It's a problem.

278
00:13:35.815 --> 00:13:36.983
-I don't have it.
-I know.

279
00:13:37.150 --> 00:13:39.652
Didn't one of you tell me that
that saying is Vince's?

280
00:13:39.819 --> 00:13:41.487
Oh. it's totally Vince. yes.

281
00:13:41.654 --> 00:13:44.091
"If enough people tell you you're drunk.
you probably ought to sit down."

282
00:13:44.115 --> 00:13:46.034
It's one of those room things.

283
00:13:46.200 --> 00:13:49.620
-I love that.
-Comes up a lot.

284
00:13:49.787 --> 00:13:52.457
There's a bunch of them
that always end up...

285
00:13:52.623 --> 00:13:53.833
...sneaking into dialogue.

286
00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:55.084
Look. he's not better.

287
00:13:55.251 --> 00:13:57.712
You guys. he's not better at all.

288
00:13:57.879 --> 00:14:01.341
-That doesn't look good.
-I love this line.

289
00:14:01.507 --> 00:14:03.259
This is not what "fine" looks like.

290
00:14:03.426 --> 00:14:05.595
-Yeah. Patrick did it so well.
-That's truth telling.

291
00:14:05.762 --> 00:14:07.138
And how great is McKean?

292
00:14:07.305 --> 00:14:09.891
-Yeah.
-Oh. God. Oh. my God.

293
00:14:10.058 --> 00:14:11.934
Hands down.

294
00:14:12.352 --> 00:14:15.772
What I like about this scene too
and the way that both of them play it...

295
00:14:15.938 --> 00:14:18.191
...is. like. they both have a point.

296
00:14:18.358 --> 00:14:21.652
It's not like... It's not like Hamlin
is just trying to maneuver him...

297
00:14:21.819 --> 00:14:24.322
...for his own end.
He really does have a point.

298
00:14:24.489 --> 00:14:28.993
Like. just retire and be
the sort of genius lawyer that you are...

299
00:14:29.160 --> 00:14:30.721
-...but for the world.
-Take care of yourself.

300
00:14:30.745 --> 00:14:33.790
-Take care of yourself. exactly.
-Do not drag the firm down with you.

301
00:14:33.956 --> 00:14:35.541
-Right.
-But that's the thing...

302
00:14:35.708 --> 00:14:38.586
...where Chuck has... That's his identity.

303
00:14:38.753 --> 00:14:41.381
But as self-righteous
and as legal-minded as he is...

304
00:14:41.547 --> 00:14:44.276
...there's no part of him that realizes.
you should not be representing...

305
00:14:44.300 --> 00:14:46.928
-...people in court right now.
-Minkie. I love this shot.

306
00:14:47.095 --> 00:14:48.405
-I just have to say.
-Look at that.

307
00:14:48.429 --> 00:14:51.682
Every time I see this shot.
with that heel coming down...

308
00:14:51.849 --> 00:14:55.061
-Can I tell you the pain getting there?
-You had to move the sun?

309
00:14:55.228 --> 00:14:56.521
-Yeah.
-Yes.

310
00:14:56.687 --> 00:15:01.067
We actually ordered a Technocrane in
and the head broke down...

311
00:15:01.234 --> 00:15:03.670
...so I had to find another way to do it
because I was not willing...

312
00:15:03.694 --> 00:15:05.822
-...to give up on that shot.
-It's so great.

313
00:15:05.988 --> 00:15:07.073
It's such a great shot.

314
00:15:08.616 --> 00:15:09.867
Tell them about the oil well.

315
00:15:10.034 --> 00:15:11.720
Bob. we showed up
and the oil well didn't work.

316
00:15:11.744 --> 00:15:14.455
-So then what did you guys do?
-Our pump jack.

317
00:15:14.622 --> 00:15:17.166
No. people controlled it.

318
00:15:17.333 --> 00:15:18.668
For the first day.

319
00:15:18.835 --> 00:15:20.294
Those are human beings.

320
00:15:20.461 --> 00:15:23.297
I'm looking out there
and I'm like. "There's six ninjas..."

321
00:15:23.464 --> 00:15:25.883
...doing this pump jack."
Like. dudes in black.

322
00:15:26.050 --> 00:15:27.593
They're pulling a rope.

323
00:15:27.760 --> 00:15:30.720
It's like something the ancient Egyptians
would've done to build a pyramid.

324
00:15:30.847 --> 00:15:32.682
-Were you erasing them?
-We erased them.

325
00:15:32.849 --> 00:15:35.184
Well. most of those pump jacks.
Bill Powloski...

326
00:15:35.351 --> 00:15:37.121
-...our wonderful VFX supervisor...
-Our visual effects.

327
00:15:37.145 --> 00:15:38.187
Most of those are digital.

328
00:15:38.354 --> 00:15:40.565
-But the one that's closest to us...
-Yeah.

329
00:15:40.731 --> 00:15:43.359
...was being operated
by human beings the whole time.

330
00:15:43.526 --> 00:15:45.695
For one day.
and the other day it worked.

331
00:15:45.862 --> 00:15:48.114
You came back from this...
Was this a one-day shoot?

332
00:15:48.281 --> 00:15:49.323
-Two days.
-Two days.

333
00:15:49.490 --> 00:15:53.578
And you came back from this
with windburn and sand burn. right?

334
00:15:53.744 --> 00:15:55.496
-Yeah.
-Yes.

335
00:15:55.663 --> 00:15:59.125
I've never had my hands
in my pockets harder in my whole life.

336
00:15:59.292 --> 00:16:01.419
-You were pooping out sand pellets?
-Yep.

337
00:16:01.586 --> 00:16:04.797
It was freezing cold. temperature-wise...

338
00:16:04.964 --> 00:16:07.091
...and then there was
some windstorm issues...

339
00:16:07.258 --> 00:16:09.302
...with. like. icy... Icy cold winds.

340
00:16:09.469 --> 00:16:11.512
-And just sandstorm.
-And then a sandstorm...

341
00:16:11.679 --> 00:16:14.849
...that was going
in the direction of our faces.

342
00:16:15.016 --> 00:16:17.268
-It doesn't look bad. does it?
-When we did the wides.

343
00:16:17.435 --> 00:16:18.519
It looks great.

344
00:16:18.686 --> 00:16:20.730
I was telling them
that Chris Mulkey and I...

345
00:16:20.897 --> 00:16:24.275
...we rehearsed. thank God.
two different nights...

346
00:16:24.859 --> 00:16:27.862
...when he got in to his hotel.

347
00:16:28.029 --> 00:16:30.406
We worked on a lot of stuff.
And Minkie was great...

348
00:16:30.573 --> 00:16:32.259
...and worked with us.
And so we understood the scene.

349
00:16:32.283 --> 00:16:35.912
But then. the wind picked up
and was making this crazy sound...

350
00:16:36.078 --> 00:16:39.582
...just where we were that was like...
Like a haunted house.

351
00:16:39.749 --> 00:16:42.309
And we couldn't hear each other.
And there was a couple points...

352
00:16:42.418 --> 00:16:44.338
...where we stared
at each other's mouths and go:

353
00:16:44.378 --> 00:16:46.297
"I think he's done talking."

354
00:16:48.216 --> 00:16:52.136
I remember looking around...
I'm standing with Gordon...

355
00:16:52.303 --> 00:16:54.514
...at this portable director's monitor.

356
00:16:54.680 --> 00:16:57.642
And the sandstorm
is really picking up speed.

357
00:16:57.808 --> 00:17:02.188
I look around and the entire crew
has suddenly got this amazing kit on.

358
00:17:02.355 --> 00:17:04.857
Sandstorm protection...

359
00:17:05.024 --> 00:17:06.317
-Goggles.
-Goggles.

360
00:17:06.484 --> 00:17:08.204
When we look over.
they were all in goggles.

361
00:17:08.236 --> 00:17:10.036
-They're amazing.
-That's an Albuquerque crew.

362
00:17:10.154 --> 00:17:12.156
Yeah. that's a <i>Breaking Bad</i> crew.

363
00:17:12.323 --> 00:17:15.910
Gordon and I looked at each other like.
"ls there something we don't know?"

364
00:17:16.077 --> 00:17:17.453
-No.
-Nothing stops them...

365
00:17:17.620 --> 00:17:21.457
-...nothing even gives them pause.
-Is that being operated by people?

366
00:17:21.624 --> 00:17:23.709
-On day one. I don't know which...
-I can't remember.

367
00:17:23.876 --> 00:17:25.395
I don't think it was operated by people.

368
00:17:25.419 --> 00:17:27.272
I think by then
they'd gotten the motor working.

369
00:17:27.296 --> 00:17:30.049
You know. we're very lucky
with sandstorms because the...

370
00:17:30.216 --> 00:17:32.927
The sandstorm you're talking about
reminds me of the one...

371
00:17:33.094 --> 00:17:36.305
...on Bob's first episode
of <i>Breaking Bad...</i>

372
00:17:36.472 --> 00:17:38.933
-...when you're crouched in front of the...
-Yeah.

373
00:17:39.100 --> 00:17:41.310
-Grave.
-In front of the grave. on your knees...

374
00:17:41.477 --> 00:17:43.771
...and there was so much sand...

375
00:17:43.938 --> 00:17:46.065
-...that you were spitting it out.
-Yeah.

376
00:17:46.232 --> 00:17:49.318
This was... Minkie said it too.
This was... It's in your eyeballs.

377
00:17:49.485 --> 00:17:50.629
-It's up your nose.
-Yeah. We had that.

378
00:17:50.653 --> 00:17:53.489
I had the medic every 10 minutes
putting saline in my eyes...

379
00:17:53.656 --> 00:17:56.242
...just so I could see.
It was just intense.

380
00:17:56.409 --> 00:17:58.786
I was so excited
to get to do one of these iconic...

381
00:17:58.953 --> 00:18:02.623
...beautiful wides. though.
And Minkie gave me the best direction...

382
00:18:02.790 --> 00:18:06.961
...here. which was just as simple as.
"In real time. I want you to figure out...

383
00:18:07.128 --> 00:18:10.590
...how to dig your car out."
And to have the luxury of. like...

384
00:18:10.756 --> 00:18:15.094
...doing that. and doing that for real.
and filming it...

385
00:18:15.261 --> 00:18:17.930
...and trusting that the audience
is staying with your character...

386
00:18:18.097 --> 00:18:20.266
...was just really great.

387
00:18:20.433 --> 00:18:22.435
This was a moment too
that we were really...

388
00:18:22.602 --> 00:18:26.063
We were trying to figure out
how to button that scene...

389
00:18:26.230 --> 00:18:30.067
...with Chris Mulkey. Gatwood. to sort of
give us a little bit more about Kim.

390
00:18:30.234 --> 00:18:31.874
When we were talking about it.
we're like:

391
00:18:31.986 --> 00:18:33.338
-He was great.
- "What would she...?"

392
00:18:33.362 --> 00:18:34.655
He's great. but we wanted...

393
00:18:34.822 --> 00:18:37.783
It felt like the scene wasn't
kind of landing...

394
00:18:37.950 --> 00:18:40.911
...in terms of learning
something new about Kim.

395
00:18:41.078 --> 00:18:44.749
And so this was what we came up with.
in terms of. like...

396
00:18:44.915 --> 00:18:48.044
...she's so driven at this point
that she won't even ask for help...

397
00:18:48.210 --> 00:18:50.796
...to get her car out of the dirt.

398
00:18:50.963 --> 00:18:52.798
-Right.
-What was amazing is. Rhea...

399
00:18:52.965 --> 00:18:54.967
-...you wanted to do it all.
-I did.

400
00:18:55.134 --> 00:18:57.595
And you pretty much did it all.
apart from one shot.

401
00:18:57.762 --> 00:19:00.723
Yes. the amazing Heather Bonomo.
my stunt double...

402
00:19:01.307 --> 00:19:05.603
...she did just that last frame
where you actually jump into the car.

403
00:19:05.770 --> 00:19:08.648
I opened the... Ran to the car.
opened the door. got a leg in...

404
00:19:08.814 --> 00:19:10.709
...but they would not let me
pull the other leg in...

405
00:19:10.733 --> 00:19:13.045
...because you could shut a door
on your leg. and insurance and all.

406
00:19:13.069 --> 00:19:14.111
But I wanted to do it.

407
00:19:14.278 --> 00:19:17.156
But Heather watched me for a day
and a half before she did that.

408
00:19:17.323 --> 00:19:18.800
-By the time she did it...
-Brilliant.

409
00:19:18.824 --> 00:19:21.035
She ran like me. she walked like me.

410
00:19:21.202 --> 00:19:22.662
It was kind of weird.

411
00:19:22.828 --> 00:19:24.664
-Yeah.
-She was great.

412
00:19:24.830 --> 00:19:26.916
There's so much to talk about
in that scene.

413
00:19:27.083 --> 00:19:30.336
-We're never gonna touch on all of it.
-I loved playing that scene.

414
00:19:30.503 --> 00:19:34.507
I just have to say. again.
the beautiful physical acting...

415
00:19:34.674 --> 00:19:36.592
-...that you did...
-Well. thanks.

416
00:19:36.759 --> 00:19:38.928
-That's a great reveal.
-It really is wonderful.

417
00:19:39.095 --> 00:19:41.055
-And then. here's...
-I love this scene...

418
00:19:41.222 --> 00:19:43.766
...between you and Patrick
so much. Bob.

419
00:19:44.266 --> 00:19:45.643
Is this about Chuck?

420
00:19:46.227 --> 00:19:47.436
Who?

421
00:19:48.104 --> 00:19:49.980
If you actually have business...

422
00:19:50.147 --> 00:19:52.858
Have you started merchandising
those ties?

423
00:19:53.025 --> 00:19:56.445
You know. it's...
I think we're gonna have to. It's...

424
00:19:56.612 --> 00:19:58.114
We're working on it.

425
00:19:58.280 --> 00:20:02.952
The Jimmy McGill collection
is really pretty awesome.

426
00:20:03.369 --> 00:20:07.581
And Jennifer Bryan has brought back
the knit tie. single-handedly.

427
00:20:07.748 --> 00:20:11.585
Yes. I believe that when she
first started shopping for them...

428
00:20:11.752 --> 00:20:14.755
...they were hard to come by.
and now they're around everywhere.

429
00:20:14.922 --> 00:20:16.465
-Oh. really?
-Yes.

430
00:20:16.632 --> 00:20:19.301
Oh. so now you're worried
about the clients?

431
00:20:19.969 --> 00:20:22.304
You two guys together...

432
00:20:22.805 --> 00:20:26.016
All you care about is
your share of the payout.

433
00:20:27.351 --> 00:20:29.395
I think Jimmy has
a really good point here.

434
00:20:29.562 --> 00:20:32.356
-They both have...
-That's what's great about the writing.

435
00:20:32.523 --> 00:20:35.860
Yes. and by the way.
fans of the show...

436
00:20:36.026 --> 00:20:39.196
...who are lawyers say that he's right.

437
00:20:39.363 --> 00:20:42.241
He's right. That when you have
old people in a suit...

438
00:20:42.408 --> 00:20:44.910
...one of the things
you change about it...

439
00:20:45.077 --> 00:20:49.957
...is you're more willing to settle it
because they are not gonna...

440
00:20:50.124 --> 00:20:53.127
-They're not gonna make it.
-Get to have the money that you're...

441
00:20:53.294 --> 00:20:55.212
...winning for them.

442
00:20:55.755 --> 00:20:57.465
And if we don't. what are you gonna do?

443
00:20:57.631 --> 00:21:00.718
At this point. Bob.
do you think Jimmy has any thought...

444
00:21:00.885 --> 00:21:03.637
...about what he's gonna do
with Mrs. Landry?

445
00:21:03.804 --> 00:21:05.389
-Or...?
-No.

446
00:21:07.433 --> 00:21:10.686
I think. you know.
Jimmy just goes through life...

447
00:21:11.270 --> 00:21:14.940
...waiting for these chasms
to open in front of him.

448
00:21:15.107 --> 00:21:19.487
And then as quick as he can.
thinks of a solution...

449
00:21:19.653 --> 00:21:22.364
...that is not airtight. ever.

450
00:21:22.531 --> 00:21:25.701
-But less premeditated. do you think?
-But still fun.

451
00:21:25.868 --> 00:21:27.578
But much less premeditated.
do you think?

452
00:21:27.745 --> 00:21:29.997
It's not. like. a big. long scheme?

453
00:21:30.164 --> 00:21:33.417
He's not... No. there's no long view.

454
00:21:33.584 --> 00:21:37.254
But I think Saul. though.
makes a longer plan.

455
00:21:37.421 --> 00:21:39.590
A bigger. longer plan.

456
00:21:39.757 --> 00:21:42.218
-That's an interesting point.
-But more care...

457
00:21:42.635 --> 00:21:45.554
More selfish.
Anyhow. my theories on the character.

458
00:21:46.055 --> 00:21:48.015
-I like that.
-Well. look at these guys.

459
00:21:48.182 --> 00:21:51.268
-It's also freezing in this scene...
-Is it. is it?

460
00:21:51.435 --> 00:21:53.270
-Oh. utterly freezing.
-It is freezing.

461
00:21:53.437 --> 00:21:56.816
This is actually where we put Gordon up
when he's staying in Albuquerque.

462
00:21:56.982 --> 00:21:58.275
-I do.
-It gets cold rain too.

463
00:21:58.442 --> 00:22:00.337
I stay in one of the barrels
that you can see in the background.

464
00:22:00.361 --> 00:22:02.863
Of course. Mando's happy.
He's got a leather jacket.

465
00:22:03.030 --> 00:22:04.073
Yep.

466
00:22:04.240 --> 00:22:07.201
I mean. Mark was very...

467
00:22:07.910 --> 00:22:10.310
...frightened about this scene.
not just about the Spanish...

468
00:22:10.371 --> 00:22:12.039
...but about... It was bitterly cold.

469
00:22:12.206 --> 00:22:14.708
He didn't know
if he'd be able to do the four hours.

470
00:22:14.875 --> 00:22:16.418
-He's an older man.
-Exactly.

471
00:22:16.585 --> 00:22:18.796
-I mean. it's genuinely...
-No. that's...

472
00:22:18.963 --> 00:22:20.965
-...scary.
-We've hired a bunch of actors...

473
00:22:21.131 --> 00:22:23.092
-...who don't speak Spanish.
-We sent him back...

474
00:22:23.259 --> 00:22:25.511
...changed his costume.
put thermals underneath.

475
00:22:25.678 --> 00:22:28.848
-Yeah. Was he okay?
-Yeah. Yeah.

476
00:22:29.014 --> 00:22:31.892
You can't do much about your face.
though. as we figured out...

477
00:22:32.059 --> 00:22:33.644
...in that last scene with me.

478
00:22:33.811 --> 00:22:35.997
You guys have been out
in the elements much more than I have.

479
00:22:36.021 --> 00:22:38.399
I'm mostly an indoor cat... Kim.

480
00:22:38.566 --> 00:22:41.986
But your lips start to freeze. And...

481
00:22:42.152 --> 00:22:44.089
-Yeah. you can't speak.
-You can't speak correctly.

482
00:22:44.113 --> 00:22:45.614
I know. You can't enunciate.

483
00:22:45.781 --> 00:22:47.658
Boy. he's fucking good.

484
00:22:47.825 --> 00:22:48.993
He's so good.

485
00:22:49.159 --> 00:22:51.912
Goddamn it. he's angry.

486
00:22:52.288 --> 00:22:55.124
The thing is. he walks around
with that anger all day.

487
00:22:55.291 --> 00:22:59.128
Now. Giancarlo. on the other hand.
is actually not at all.

488
00:22:59.295 --> 00:23:02.631
No. he will give you meditative. like...

489
00:23:02.798 --> 00:23:05.509
...beautiful spiritual talks
and stuff in between.

490
00:23:05.676 --> 00:23:07.803
Yeah. and Margolis is genuinely...

491
00:23:08.596 --> 00:23:10.806
He could kill someone.

492
00:23:12.349 --> 00:23:14.435
-What's so funny?
-He's gonna kill us all.

493
00:23:16.228 --> 00:23:18.314
I love watching Giancarlo...

494
00:23:19.648 --> 00:23:22.526
...find the nuances
of who Gus Fring was...

495
00:23:22.693 --> 00:23:25.112
...just a few years before. you know?

496
00:23:25.279 --> 00:23:29.241
It's not this huge leap.
but it's not where he ends up.

497
00:23:30.200 --> 00:23:33.996
He's just fascinating to watch.
no matter what's happening.

498
00:23:34.163 --> 00:23:36.582
-He is.
-It's with all you guys.

499
00:23:36.749 --> 00:23:39.960
And it's something you kind of learn
almost second by second...

500
00:23:40.127 --> 00:23:45.257
...in the editing room.
is that we see so much on your faces...

501
00:23:46.091 --> 00:23:47.259
...from moment to moment.

502
00:23:47.426 --> 00:23:49.426
And there's always
something interesting to cut to.

503
00:23:49.511 --> 00:23:51.448
In fact. one of the problems
in the editing room is often...

504
00:23:51.472 --> 00:23:52.952
...you wanna be looking at everybody.

505
00:23:53.140 --> 00:23:56.936
You wanna be seeing
everything that's happening.

506
00:23:57.102 --> 00:24:00.898
And this scene also was shot
with the VariCam...

507
00:24:01.065 --> 00:24:05.486
...that we've talked about in other...
Other commentary tracks.

508
00:24:10.491 --> 00:24:12.409
Here we are at the mall.

509
00:24:13.577 --> 00:24:16.038
-Those shoes are ridiculous.
-Yeah.

510
00:24:16.205 --> 00:24:18.749
-MBTs.
-Are those hard to walk in?

511
00:24:18.916 --> 00:24:21.543
They don't make them anymore.
I think. right?

512
00:24:21.710 --> 00:24:23.253
-Are they comfortable?
-They do.

513
00:24:23.420 --> 00:24:25.714
-No. They're a joke.
-They do make them...

514
00:24:25.881 --> 00:24:27.549
...but we went back. I think. to...

515
00:24:27.716 --> 00:24:28.759
They're not...

516
00:24:28.926 --> 00:24:31.762
The rocking heel toe
does not look comfortable to me.

517
00:24:31.929 --> 00:24:33.222
But. Bob. you are so lovely.

518
00:24:33.389 --> 00:24:35.474
You made sure
that Jean had them in advance...

519
00:24:35.641 --> 00:24:38.435
...so that she could test them
and feel comfortable in them.

520
00:24:38.602 --> 00:24:41.438
Well. I like these ladies.
They're all super-awesome.

521
00:24:41.605 --> 00:24:44.149
-You were amazing with them.
-Jean Effron is...

522
00:24:44.316 --> 00:24:48.153
...an outstanding person.
besides being a great actress.

523
00:24:48.320 --> 00:24:50.739
MBT actually asked for this clip
on their website.

524
00:24:50.906 --> 00:24:52.533
-No.
-Yes.

525
00:24:52.700 --> 00:24:54.243
-Wonderful.
-We appreciate them...

526
00:24:54.410 --> 00:24:57.246
...helping us out with the shoes.

527
00:24:57.413 --> 00:25:01.917
This is so funny. guys.
to do this phony baloney.

528
00:25:02.334 --> 00:25:04.753
-It's so ridiculous.
-It's so fun.

529
00:25:04.920 --> 00:25:06.880
"Oh. yeah. I love it.
Are you kidding me?"

530
00:25:07.047 --> 00:25:08.132
"Hey. what's going on?"

531
00:25:08.298 --> 00:25:10.009
Who doesn't love the mall walk?

532
00:25:10.175 --> 00:25:11.802
Look at the suit he's in.

533
00:25:11.969 --> 00:25:13.721
And the red headband.

534
00:25:13.887 --> 00:25:16.557
You know.
when we do stuff like this. Peter...

535
00:25:16.724 --> 00:25:19.143
...do you guys have
conversations about...

536
00:25:19.309 --> 00:25:21.687
Because I'm thinking you know...

537
00:25:21.854 --> 00:25:23.355
...how I would like to go...

538
00:25:24.273 --> 00:25:28.986
...just another 15 percent further
into stupidity.

539
00:25:29.403 --> 00:25:30.571
Just because...

540
00:25:30.738 --> 00:25:31.780
You must think. like...

541
00:25:31.947 --> 00:25:34.324
So the tone meetings
are just about reining you in?

542
00:25:34.491 --> 00:25:36.368
-Is that what it is?
-Just the opposite. Bob.

543
00:25:36.535 --> 00:25:39.621
In my brain... The tone meeting
in my brain is about...

544
00:25:39.788 --> 00:25:41.290
...you can't go that far.

545
00:25:41.707 --> 00:25:44.752
But... Like this. look how cocky he is.

546
00:25:44.918 --> 00:25:47.671
Yeah. sure. laughs.

547
00:25:48.464 --> 00:25:51.508
-I'll tell you. that used to worry me.
-Just easygoing. you know?

548
00:25:51.675 --> 00:25:54.094
It worried me about Saul
on <i>Breaking Bad.</i>

549
00:25:54.261 --> 00:25:57.389
Is this tone gonna work
with the rest of the show?

550
00:25:57.556 --> 00:25:59.141
That was something I was worried...

551
00:25:59.308 --> 00:26:04.188
I'm not worried at all anymore.
Because it's just our world and it works.

552
00:26:04.354 --> 00:26:05.856
It does.

553
00:26:06.023 --> 00:26:10.611
And I don't feel like
you've ever put a wrong foot. ever.

554
00:26:10.778 --> 00:26:12.071
This is so ridiculous.

555
00:26:12.237 --> 00:26:13.864
And yet it feels effortless.

556
00:26:14.031 --> 00:26:16.909
Yeah. I mean.
Vince even left that thing in...

557
00:26:17.076 --> 00:26:20.370
...where I leaned
on the soda machine in that first...

558
00:26:20.537 --> 00:26:22.164
Oh. that's so great.

559
00:26:22.331 --> 00:26:26.543
Which I thought. as fun as it was to do.
and it was super-fun to do...

560
00:26:26.960 --> 00:26:29.963
...there's no way it can stay in.

561
00:26:30.130 --> 00:26:32.007
But I thought it was fine.

562
00:26:32.174 --> 00:26:33.509
Perfect.

563
00:26:35.219 --> 00:26:38.806
Yeah. I mean. you guys...
We are so lucky...

564
00:26:38.972 --> 00:26:43.018
...to have the latitude we have
to do comedy.

565
00:26:43.185 --> 00:26:44.686
And right next to...

566
00:26:45.104 --> 00:26:47.481
We're so lucky we have actors that...

567
00:26:47.648 --> 00:26:50.400
-That can do it.
-That have that affinity. Yeah.

568
00:26:50.567 --> 00:26:54.905
Obviously. we wouldn't be here
if you weren't here. Bob.

569
00:26:55.072 --> 00:26:58.617
-Well. thanks.
-If you hadn't started on <i>Breaking Bad...</i>

570
00:26:58.784 --> 00:27:00.869
...none of us would be here right now.

571
00:27:01.036 --> 00:27:03.831
-This guy is so great.
-Yeah. it's so great.

572
00:27:03.997 --> 00:27:06.142
-I was so happy about this.
-What is that clip. Gordon?

573
00:27:06.166 --> 00:27:07.751
That is <i>Night of the Hunted.</i>

574
00:27:07.918 --> 00:27:10.003
<i>-Night of the Hunter.</i>
-Sorry. different movie.

575
00:27:10.170 --> 00:27:11.922
-Yeah. Mitchum.
-Robert Mitchum...

576
00:27:12.089 --> 00:27:16.176
...explaining the story of love and hate.
the tattoos that he has on his knuckles.

577
00:27:16.343 --> 00:27:18.345
The only movie directed
by Charles Laughton.

578
00:27:18.512 --> 00:27:19.888
-Really?
-Yes.

579
00:27:20.055 --> 00:27:22.933
-And it's so good. He did a great job.
-So good.

580
00:27:23.100 --> 00:27:25.060
Feels very appropriate.

581
00:27:25.227 --> 00:27:26.812
This montage...

582
00:27:28.147 --> 00:27:30.315
By the way.
I want to give a lot of credit...

583
00:27:30.482 --> 00:27:33.026
...to Skip Macdonald.
who cut this episode.

584
00:27:33.193 --> 00:27:34.611
Wow. Skip.

585
00:27:34.778 --> 00:27:38.782
Skip is just a one-of-a-kind talent.
He's amazing.

586
00:27:39.700 --> 00:27:41.952
But also. Minkie just shot
the hell out of this.

587
00:27:42.119 --> 00:27:45.581
Yeah. coming out of the faces of
the ladies in the mall with the color...

588
00:27:45.747 --> 00:27:48.208
...into that ball rolling in.

589
00:27:48.375 --> 00:27:52.045
I mean. it was really something.
This is an amazing piece of editing.

590
00:27:52.504 --> 00:27:54.548
Now. I heard a story about a balloon.

591
00:27:55.048 --> 00:27:57.384
-Yes.
-What's the story about the balloon?

592
00:27:57.551 --> 00:28:00.262
I wanted those transitions
as much as possible so that...

593
00:28:00.429 --> 00:28:02.472
...you know. Skip would have the...

594
00:28:02.890 --> 00:28:05.142
The ingredients to then play.

595
00:28:05.309 --> 00:28:07.477
There was this issue
with our Art Department...

596
00:28:07.644 --> 00:28:09.372
...that those kind of things
didn't exist in the mall.

597
00:28:09.396 --> 00:28:11.440
I was like. "Just fuck it.
You know what...

598
00:28:11.607 --> 00:28:14.776
...at this point. it's not about reality.
It's about the montage."

599
00:28:14.943 --> 00:28:18.906
So you had a blue balloon
up in the mall that matched a blue...

600
00:28:19.698 --> 00:28:22.117
-Billiard ball.
-The number two billiard ball. yeah.

601
00:28:22.284 --> 00:28:25.204
The timing of getting lovely Jean
to walk through...

602
00:28:25.370 --> 00:28:27.831
...at the same time
that the camera. it was...

603
00:28:27.998 --> 00:28:29.958
I didn't even know you were doing that.

604
00:28:30.125 --> 00:28:32.961
I was no help on that day. It's...

605
00:28:33.128 --> 00:28:35.839
-The music is also wonderful.
-The music is awesome.

606
00:28:36.006 --> 00:28:37.674
The upbeat music. yeah.

607
00:28:37.841 --> 00:28:41.803
We have Ann Harper
running the yoga session here...

608
00:28:41.970 --> 00:28:44.932
...who is Rich Sickler's wife. our AD.

609
00:28:45.098 --> 00:28:47.059
An incredible masseuse...
Massage therapist.

610
00:28:47.226 --> 00:28:48.685
-Indeed.
-Yes. she is.

611
00:28:48.852 --> 00:28:50.896
Oh. wait a minute. I didn't know that.

612
00:28:51.063 --> 00:28:52.814
Hey. look at the big picture.

613
00:28:55.234 --> 00:28:57.027
Oh. man.

614
00:28:57.194 --> 00:28:59.696
This is a great advertisement
for chair yoga. I think.

615
00:28:59.863 --> 00:29:01.281
-It is.
-I would do it.

616
00:29:01.448 --> 00:29:02.491
Poor Jean.

617
00:29:02.658 --> 00:29:05.118
Jennifer Bryan's costumes are so great.

618
00:29:05.285 --> 00:29:08.038
-They are.
-They won't even talk to her.

619
00:29:08.205 --> 00:29:14.253
It was a real challenge
to try and shoot four days...

620
00:29:14.419 --> 00:29:15.712
...with senior citizens.

621
00:29:15.879 --> 00:29:17.589
Having to get them
to change costumes...

622
00:29:17.756 --> 00:29:21.718
...within the two-hour time frame we
were allowed in the mall. but we did it.

623
00:29:21.885 --> 00:29:24.554
You had to be in the mall
at an ungodly early hour. right?

624
00:29:24.721 --> 00:29:25.973
Four days to shoot?

625
00:29:26.139 --> 00:29:27.499
-Two days. Two mornings.
-Two days.

626
00:29:27.599 --> 00:29:29.142
You could only shoot till 10.

627
00:29:29.309 --> 00:29:31.728
Yeah. that's why we had to do it
over two days...

628
00:29:31.895 --> 00:29:33.455
...because we didn't have enough hours.

629
00:29:33.563 --> 00:29:35.691
-Did you really?
-I think we had a company move...

630
00:29:35.857 --> 00:29:39.194
...almost every single day
of this shoot and some days two.

631
00:29:39.361 --> 00:29:42.155
Which is... It's a lot
because it eats up a lot of time.

632
00:29:42.322 --> 00:29:44.908
A challenging show... Episode.

633
00:29:45.075 --> 00:29:48.412
Minkie. wow. it's amazing what you did.

634
00:29:48.578 --> 00:29:51.331
-Thank you. Bob.
-This scene... Who plays his dad?

635
00:29:51.498 --> 00:29:53.667
-This is Juan Carlos Cantu.
-I love him.

636
00:29:53.834 --> 00:29:55.294
-And he is...
-So amazing.

637
00:29:55.460 --> 00:29:56.545
I love him so much.

638
00:29:56.712 --> 00:30:00.340
These two guys.
Michael and Juan Carlos are just...

639
00:30:00.507 --> 00:30:03.635
Michael is just beautiful
and brilliant in this episode.

640
00:30:03.802 --> 00:30:07.389
It was really interesting. because
Michael's instinct was to walk around...

641
00:30:07.556 --> 00:30:09.599
...and be very animated.

642
00:30:09.766 --> 00:30:13.520
We had a long chat with him.
took about 45 minutes during lunch...

643
00:30:13.687 --> 00:30:16.648
...just sit with him and Juan
to just talk about stillness.

644
00:30:17.566 --> 00:30:19.151
He's so powerful when he's still.

645
00:30:19.318 --> 00:30:21.153
-It's great.
-Yeah.

646
00:30:21.486 --> 00:30:24.197
Once he embraced it.
he went with it amazingly.

647
00:30:25.657 --> 00:30:29.244
Yeah. we had a long slow lead-up
of him getting that milk...

648
00:30:29.411 --> 00:30:31.806
...and coming in and how he was
in the space. which was great.

649
00:30:31.830 --> 00:30:32.956
But we didn't have time.

650
00:30:33.123 --> 00:30:36.335
The episode was so long. so...
But it was great.

651
00:30:36.501 --> 00:30:39.296
It was that stillness.
sort of him moving slowly...

652
00:30:39.463 --> 00:30:41.631
...through this space and coming to rest.

653
00:30:41.798 --> 00:30:46.678
It's painful to get
these episodes close to time. this...

654
00:30:47.054 --> 00:30:49.890
Because there's just
so much great material in them.

655
00:30:50.057 --> 00:30:52.601
This scene.
it's an interesting scene for us...

656
00:30:52.768 --> 00:30:56.563
...because there's no ironic subtext.

657
00:30:56.730 --> 00:30:58.815
There's nothing funny about it.

658
00:30:58.982 --> 00:31:01.443
It's very straight-ahead.

659
00:31:01.610 --> 00:31:05.113
It's a very honest.
straight-ahead scene.

660
00:31:05.280 --> 00:31:07.949
And we have a run of them
in these last couple episodes...

661
00:31:08.116 --> 00:31:11.078
...where there's a lot more honesty
than we're used to having.

662
00:31:11.244 --> 00:31:15.499
And I think it's really beautiful.

663
00:31:15.665 --> 00:31:18.418
But hopefully it feels like
we've earned it by this point.

664
00:31:18.585 --> 00:31:22.381
Like. that was... When we were
talking about this scene. it was like...

665
00:31:22.839 --> 00:31:24.424
...the bill has come due.

666
00:31:24.591 --> 00:31:27.344
He's gotta have this conversation
he's been avoiding...

667
00:31:27.511 --> 00:31:30.680
...for a long. long time with his father.

668
00:31:30.847 --> 00:31:34.601
But the only way to do it
is to do it straightforward.

669
00:31:35.060 --> 00:31:36.520
-So...
-There's...

670
00:31:36.686 --> 00:31:39.106
And of course.
Michael is not a Spanish-speaker.

671
00:31:39.272 --> 00:31:43.819
And I'm not either. so I can't talk
about his Spanish. but I can say...

672
00:31:43.985 --> 00:31:46.029
And neither is Mark Margolis.
doing Hector.

673
00:31:46.196 --> 00:31:48.949
-The commitment they both have...
-Or Giancarlo.

674
00:31:49.116 --> 00:31:50.367
-Or Giancarlo.
-Yeah.

675
00:31:50.534 --> 00:31:53.578
Their commitment
to the dialect coaches and studying...

676
00:31:53.745 --> 00:31:55.390
...and not just wanting
to speak Spanish...

677
00:31:55.414 --> 00:32:00.752
...but speak Cuban or Mexican
or street is just phenomenal.

678
00:32:00.919 --> 00:32:03.338
And our apologies
to Spanish-speakers if we...

679
00:32:03.505 --> 00:32:05.590
If we miss something or mess up.

680
00:32:05.757 --> 00:32:08.009
But I think...

681
00:32:08.718 --> 00:32:10.429
This particular scene is especially...

682
00:32:10.595 --> 00:32:14.850
I gotta tell you. I couldn't help but think
about Michael and his real dad.

683
00:32:15.016 --> 00:32:17.102
-Yeah?
-Because his dad is a huge presence...

684
00:32:17.269 --> 00:32:21.189
...in his life
and has a real amazing story.

685
00:32:21.356 --> 00:32:25.485
Michael's life story
and the dad's story. the way they're...

686
00:32:25.652 --> 00:32:29.156
The two stories
and the way they come together...

687
00:32:29.322 --> 00:32:30.532
...is really powerful.

688
00:32:30.699 --> 00:32:32.325
And it's a big part of him.

689
00:32:32.492 --> 00:32:34.995
And so this scene.
I couldn't help but think about...

690
00:32:35.162 --> 00:32:36.872
...everything he's told me about his dad.

691
00:32:37.038 --> 00:32:38.358
You guys should ask him about it.

692
00:32:38.415 --> 00:32:41.543
It's really interesting you say that.
because he got so emotional.

693
00:32:41.710 --> 00:32:45.422
-Oh. yeah.
-And I kept on asking him to hold back.

694
00:32:45.589 --> 00:32:48.383
Well. it's really true.
I mean. I think his father...

695
00:32:48.550 --> 00:32:51.636
If he was to really disappoint
his own father...

696
00:32:51.803 --> 00:32:54.639
...it would be the worst thing in his life.

697
00:32:58.685 --> 00:33:02.189
I actually had him
have paper towels in his lap...

698
00:33:02.355 --> 00:33:03.899
...so he could wipe his tears.

699
00:33:04.065 --> 00:33:07.027
Because he couldn't help himself.
and it makes more sense now.

700
00:33:07.194 --> 00:33:11.948
Yeah. it's a great story and I would love
to tell it. but it's his to tell.

701
00:33:12.115 --> 00:33:14.868
You could ask him about it
when he does the...

702
00:33:15.035 --> 00:33:17.370
Tell us a little
about your dad or something.

703
00:33:17.537 --> 00:33:19.873
Because it'd be something to hear.

704
00:33:20.040 --> 00:33:22.751
I'm always happy
when Audrey Moore is in the show.

705
00:33:22.918 --> 00:33:25.670
-She's just...
-And here comes Fabian here...

706
00:33:25.837 --> 00:33:28.673
...and not what he expects.
It's so great.

707
00:33:28.840 --> 00:33:31.760
"He's retiring. he listened to me.
What a good guy."

708
00:33:31.927 --> 00:33:34.095
I believe
this was shot at night. wasn't it?

709
00:33:34.262 --> 00:33:35.388
-Yes.
-Yeah.

710
00:33:35.555 --> 00:33:38.266
We had to shift things around
a little bit so that...

711
00:33:38.433 --> 00:33:40.644
-This was one of our problem spots.
-Yes.

712
00:33:40.810 --> 00:33:43.230
-Yes.
-But you'd never know. I mean...

713
00:33:43.396 --> 00:33:44.564
-No.
-It looks perfect.

714
00:33:44.731 --> 00:33:47.442
Steve Litecky. our gaffer.
had to make some magic.

715
00:33:47.609 --> 00:33:51.363
All right. so this is
Fabian's Emmy episode.

716
00:33:51.530 --> 00:33:53.031
It is. right?

717
00:33:53.198 --> 00:33:55.534
He's got a great scene in 10 too.

718
00:33:55.700 --> 00:33:58.286
-Yeah. right? Yes.
-Yeah.

719
00:33:59.120 --> 00:34:02.666
-He's gonna have to choose.
- "I'm back to normal."

720
00:34:02.832 --> 00:34:06.628
"Hi. look at me stirring.
Look how normal I'm stirring."

721
00:34:06.795 --> 00:34:09.172
I love watching this.

722
00:34:09.339 --> 00:34:11.258
This makes me laugh so much.

723
00:34:11.424 --> 00:34:12.467
So good.

724
00:34:12.634 --> 00:34:15.220
In a two-room office
when I joined him.

725
00:34:15.387 --> 00:34:18.098
And you. I tutored for the bar exam.

726
00:34:18.265 --> 00:34:19.641
You're not kicking me out.

727
00:34:19.808 --> 00:34:23.436
If you can't "trust my judgment."
as you say. so be it...

728
00:34:23.603 --> 00:34:25.438
He's not gonna take anything
lying down.

729
00:34:25.605 --> 00:34:27.524
-No.
-Michael. Amazing.

730
00:34:27.691 --> 00:34:30.735
-And as usual. they both have a point.
-Yeah.

731
00:34:30.902 --> 00:34:33.530
Just the... I love what Patrick does here.

732
00:34:33.697 --> 00:34:35.991
You'd rather tear down HHM than retire?

733
00:34:36.157 --> 00:34:39.035
You think I'm trouble now
as your partner?

734
00:34:39.202 --> 00:34:40.704
Imagine me as your enemy.

735
00:34:43.748 --> 00:34:46.293
-The mixer
-The blender.

736
00:34:46.459 --> 00:34:50.171
He was so reticent to use that mixer.
because he just can't deal with props...

737
00:34:50.338 --> 00:34:52.138
...when he's dealing
with something emotional.

738
00:34:52.173 --> 00:34:55.677
I said. "Just try it. Just go for it.
because it's such a great addition."

739
00:34:55.844 --> 00:34:57.804
It's so good.

740
00:34:59.806 --> 00:35:02.726
And you can see that little scar
on top of his eyebrow.

741
00:35:02.892 --> 00:35:06.354
I love that he planned... That he's
been waiting to do this little show.

742
00:35:06.521 --> 00:35:09.774
Oh. yeah. "I have a glass of wine.
and I'm so relaxed.

743
00:35:09.941 --> 00:35:12.319
I'm just gonna emulsify."

744
00:35:14.529 --> 00:35:16.031
He's so specific. I love it.

745
00:35:16.197 --> 00:35:22.162
And then he calls a service
to take the pots off the stove.

746
00:35:25.999 --> 00:35:28.668
Using one of his therapeutic techniques.

747
00:35:28.835 --> 00:35:31.921
-That's right.
-A real technique. I understand. yeah.

748
00:35:32.088 --> 00:35:34.841
That was Heather Marion's discovery.
that technique.

749
00:35:35.008 --> 00:35:37.636
And. boy. it's been playing great for us.

750
00:35:37.802 --> 00:35:40.573
-Another bit of visual effects there.
-I was fascinated by the science...

751
00:35:40.597 --> 00:35:42.432
...behind this scam.

752
00:35:42.599 --> 00:35:44.684
-Yeah.
-Who came up with it?

753
00:35:44.851 --> 00:35:46.770
Oh. we never know. I couldn't tell you.

754
00:35:46.936 --> 00:35:50.398
We talked about ideas
and. like. how you would do this.

755
00:35:50.565 --> 00:35:53.151
Or how you would do
some version of this. We pitched out...

756
00:35:53.318 --> 00:35:55.236
-This is a tricky one. guys.
-Yeah.

757
00:35:55.403 --> 00:35:56.988
When in doubt. use a magnet.

758
00:35:57.155 --> 00:35:58.990
-That's our motto.
-Thank the audience...

759
00:35:59.157 --> 00:36:02.285
-It was not an easy...
-...for being part of this storytelling.

760
00:36:02.452 --> 00:36:04.292
But the magnetic paint part of it.
that ball...

761
00:36:04.454 --> 00:36:08.500
...is actually just coated on the inside
with the magnetic paint that they...

762
00:36:08.667 --> 00:36:11.378
-That's pretty strong.
-Yeah. so...

763
00:36:11.544 --> 00:36:13.731
I always had in the back of my mind
that this was a scam...

764
00:36:13.755 --> 00:36:16.341
...that Jimmy learned
from somewhere. maybe.

765
00:36:16.508 --> 00:36:19.344
I would think so. It doesn't seem like
he would've invented it. right?

766
00:36:19.511 --> 00:36:22.806
-It seems like an old carnie trick.
-That's a nice choice. Minkie...

767
00:36:22.972 --> 00:36:25.225
-...that transition.
-Oh. it's beautiful. Minkie.

768
00:36:25.392 --> 00:36:27.977
Back to our beautiful bingo hall.

769
00:36:29.479 --> 00:36:31.064
Yeah. there's...

770
00:36:31.898 --> 00:36:33.817
...another great cutting sequence here.

771
00:36:35.985 --> 00:36:41.282
We had a room full of senior citizens
who. on the face of it...

772
00:36:41.449 --> 00:36:44.285
...we were told would not be able
to hold the day.

773
00:36:44.452 --> 00:36:47.789
But. Bob. your constant...

774
00:36:47.956 --> 00:36:49.833
-Badgering?
-Crowd work?

775
00:36:49.999 --> 00:36:51.710
Patter. it just sold it.

776
00:36:51.876 --> 00:36:52.919
They didn't leave.

777
00:36:53.086 --> 00:36:55.338
They all stood there.
They stayed with us...

778
00:36:55.505 --> 00:36:58.258
...for the whole day. thanks to you.

779
00:36:58.633 --> 00:36:59.843
Well...

780
00:37:00.009 --> 00:37:01.803
...they were all great people.

781
00:37:01.970 --> 00:37:04.597
I've worked with many of them
more than once.

782
00:37:04.764 --> 00:37:08.685
And if you tell people
what's happening...

783
00:37:08.852 --> 00:37:12.439
I think with film-making. the hardest
thing is the repetitive nature.

784
00:37:12.605 --> 00:37:17.318
But if you talk them through it.
they can feel like they're a part of it.

785
00:37:17.485 --> 00:37:21.364
Oh. that lady is so funny.
What's her name?

786
00:37:21.531 --> 00:37:22.866
-Is it...?
-Which one?

787
00:37:24.659 --> 00:37:25.785
Phyllis Applegate.

788
00:37:26.953 --> 00:37:28.872
Phyllis with the wig.

789
00:37:29.038 --> 00:37:30.331
-Yes. yep.
-Right?

790
00:37:30.498 --> 00:37:31.541
Phyllis is so funny.

791
00:37:31.708 --> 00:37:34.002
We have Christopher Hagen here.
as Big Paul...

792
00:37:34.169 --> 00:37:37.046
...who auditioned for us many.
many times through the years.

793
00:37:37.213 --> 00:37:38.673
And he has such a great face.

794
00:37:38.840 --> 00:37:42.051
His excitement was
kind of extraordinary. I loved it.

795
00:37:42.218 --> 00:37:43.970
-Yeah.
-Look at that.

796
00:37:44.345 --> 00:37:47.182
Yeah. that's not the role
I thought he would win. But he did.

797
00:37:47.348 --> 00:37:49.392
No. but it worked for him.

798
00:37:49.559 --> 00:37:51.686
And there's Kelley Lewallen...

799
00:37:51.853 --> 00:37:53.980
...who also was
introduced to us season one.

800
00:37:54.814 --> 00:37:57.859
-Yes.
-She's got a wonderful deadpan humor.

801
00:37:58.026 --> 00:38:00.111
I was... I had...

802
00:38:00.278 --> 00:38:02.280
One of the scenes
I'm most proud of. ever...

803
00:38:02.447 --> 00:38:06.075
...on the directing side.
is Bob's breakdown...

804
00:38:06.242 --> 00:38:08.578
-Oh. right. the monologue.
-Breakdown at bingo.

805
00:38:08.745 --> 00:38:09.788
That was great.

806
00:38:09.954 --> 00:38:14.167
Yeah. which is really
a highlight of my film-making life.

807
00:38:14.584 --> 00:38:18.797
And so. it was so much fun
to see bingo back and to see...

808
00:38:18.963 --> 00:38:23.301
But it's also so horrible.
because Jimmy's taking something...

809
00:38:23.468 --> 00:38:27.806
...that really was positive.
that's good. that he's using...

810
00:38:27.972 --> 00:38:31.559
He was using his abilities
in more or less a positive way.

811
00:38:31.726 --> 00:38:35.146
And now it's all kind of curdling up.

812
00:38:35.313 --> 00:38:39.317
And it's fun to watch. but it's...
There's also a sadness to it...

813
00:38:39.484 --> 00:38:40.693
...to me. anyway.

814
00:38:40.860 --> 00:38:43.905
Yes. very much so.
I love the line. "I sold my soul."

815
00:38:44.072 --> 00:38:45.365
-Yeah.
-Yes.

816
00:38:45.532 --> 00:38:48.284
Because it meant very little to me
when I did it...

817
00:38:48.451 --> 00:38:51.621
...but then.
in the context of this moment...

818
00:38:52.330 --> 00:38:55.166
And we have the woman
who acts as the director...

819
00:38:55.333 --> 00:38:59.254
...at this actual facility
playing a background role.

820
00:38:59.420 --> 00:39:00.630
-Oh. yeah?
-Which was nice.

821
00:39:00.797 --> 00:39:03.550
We had a lady that had
just celebrated her 100th birthday.

822
00:39:03.716 --> 00:39:04.759
-That's right.
-Really?

823
00:39:04.926 --> 00:39:05.969
Yeah.

824
00:39:06.511 --> 00:39:09.806
Minkie. how many freaking setups
is this scene?

825
00:39:09.973 --> 00:39:11.432
Two.

826
00:39:14.018 --> 00:39:16.479
-A lot.
-How long did you take to shoot this?

827
00:39:16.646 --> 00:39:18.398
Bob. you were... You were game...

828
00:39:18.565 --> 00:39:20.733
...because it was a big ask on you.
wasn't it?

829
00:39:20.900 --> 00:39:22.443
I guess so. I don't know. though.

830
00:39:22.610 --> 00:39:24.529
That's the show.
This is what the show is.

831
00:39:24.696 --> 00:39:26.590
I know I was shooting
on the last day of the episode...

832
00:39:26.614 --> 00:39:29.617
...and you guys were doing
a separate set with just the balls...

833
00:39:29.784 --> 00:39:32.078
-...and the machinery.
-We couldn't fit that in.

834
00:39:32.245 --> 00:39:34.873
Forty-eight for "Dewey defeats Truman."

835
00:39:35.039 --> 00:39:39.252
It's... It's a shrewd question you asked.
Rhea. because...

836
00:39:39.419 --> 00:39:43.172
-It looks like 1000 setups.
-This is a very complex sequence.

837
00:39:43.339 --> 00:39:46.467
And. you know.
I think one of the things...

838
00:39:46.634 --> 00:39:49.846
...that makes a sequence complex
is if you're in the head...

839
00:39:50.013 --> 00:39:51.681
...of more than one person.

840
00:39:51.848 --> 00:39:55.518
And the fact that we're in Jimmy's head.
we're in Irene's head.

841
00:39:55.685 --> 00:39:58.396
We have all these little interactions
with Irene's friends.

842
00:39:58.563 --> 00:40:01.733
-Right.
-It's just... It's just a hell of a lot.

843
00:40:01.900 --> 00:40:05.028
Right. If it's only one
or if you're watching it...

844
00:40:05.194 --> 00:40:08.239
-...from outside. it's simpler.
-Yep.

845
00:40:08.406 --> 00:40:11.576
You have to feel all the pressures
of each of these different...

846
00:40:11.743 --> 00:40:13.786
-Also keeping... Exactly...
-Look at that face.

847
00:40:13.953 --> 00:40:16.748
Keeping everyone else alive.
keeping what they're thinking alive...

848
00:40:16.915 --> 00:40:19.918
...but not being in their heads.
But... You know what I mean?

849
00:40:20.084 --> 00:40:22.921
The only way we could make it work
was to have three cameras that day.

850
00:40:23.421 --> 00:40:25.173
-You did have three cameras?
-Yeah.

851
00:40:25.340 --> 00:40:26.966
Oh. I... I believe it.

852
00:40:27.133 --> 00:40:29.552
-It's... And it's...
-Wonderful Bonnie.

853
00:40:29.719 --> 00:40:32.764
It came out great. Yeah. Bonnie's great.

854
00:40:32.931 --> 00:40:35.725
It is a bingo for Irene!

855
00:40:35.892 --> 00:40:39.979
But it just meant that Marshall. DP.
had to compromise slightly at times...

856
00:40:40.146 --> 00:40:42.706
-...because we were having to...
-You'd be in each other's frame?

857
00:40:42.732 --> 00:40:44.442
-Yeah.
-Yeah.

858
00:40:45.443 --> 00:40:47.320
Fastest bingo of the night.

859
00:40:47.487 --> 00:40:50.823
I can't even watch this.
It just makes me squirm.

860
00:40:50.990 --> 00:40:53.159
-Heartbreaking.
-I've gotten a lot of people...

861
00:40:53.326 --> 00:40:56.621
...saying that I must be a terrible person
to my grandparents because...

862
00:40:56.788 --> 00:40:59.749
-No. I like my grandparents.
-You are a terrible person. though.

863
00:40:59.916 --> 00:41:01.226
-I am a terrible person. but...
-Genny Hutchison said on Twitter...

864
00:41:01.250 --> 00:41:02.895
...that Irene was based
on her grandmother. right?

865
00:41:02.919 --> 00:41:05.421
-Well. the name was. yeah.
-Oh. the name.

866
00:41:05.588 --> 00:41:07.799
I know she loved her
and she just passed away.

867
00:41:07.966 --> 00:41:10.551
She said that on Twitter.
so I can say that.

868
00:41:12.720 --> 00:41:15.348
This is. I think.
one of my favorite scenes...

869
00:41:15.515 --> 00:41:17.433
...we did this season.

870
00:41:17.934 --> 00:41:19.852
It's just awful.

871
00:41:20.019 --> 00:41:22.772
This must've been
a very nuanced thing to direct. Minkie.

872
00:41:22.939 --> 00:41:25.108
There's a lot of ways
you could play this scene.

873
00:41:25.274 --> 00:41:29.445
Yeah. and I think... I think for Jean.
she was very...

874
00:41:29.946 --> 00:41:33.074
She didn't want to go there.
She didn't want to get emotional.

875
00:41:33.241 --> 00:41:36.202
She struggles to get emotional. but I...

876
00:41:36.369 --> 00:41:40.540
...felt that she needed to at this point.
that we'd pushed her that far.

877
00:41:41.374 --> 00:41:44.377
What? No.

878
00:41:44.544 --> 00:41:46.254
Yes.

879
00:41:47.338 --> 00:41:48.965
They're so cold.

880
00:41:49.132 --> 00:41:50.591
Now we're watching the scene...

881
00:41:50.758 --> 00:41:52.760
-...which proves something.
-Yeah. I know.

882
00:41:52.927 --> 00:41:54.095
-It just...
-It's riveting.

883
00:41:54.262 --> 00:41:58.891
-Bob. you're so good in this.
-Jimmy is such a shit heel here.

884
00:41:59.058 --> 00:42:00.810
-Yes. he is.
-But for some reason...

885
00:42:00.977 --> 00:42:02.937
-...I can't take my eyes off him.
-No.

886
00:42:03.104 --> 00:42:06.691
-And I think it's because of you.
-Well. he... He does feel bad for her.

887
00:42:06.858 --> 00:42:10.778
See. you could see he...
"Am I doing this?"

888
00:42:10.945 --> 00:42:12.655
Yes. slight wince.

889
00:42:12.822 --> 00:42:15.199
"Am I really gonna do this?"

890
00:42:15.366 --> 00:42:18.536
Also. what he says here
is a gentle way and a kind of...

891
00:42:18.703 --> 00:42:20.329
He's using the truth.

892
00:42:20.496 --> 00:42:22.373
-Yes.
-Maybe they need the money.

893
00:42:22.540 --> 00:42:24.876
Oh. my God.
your fake. like. "I don't know."

894
00:42:25.043 --> 00:42:26.627
I don't know.

895
00:42:26.794 --> 00:42:28.880
But this is something
I find so interesting...

896
00:42:29.047 --> 00:42:31.150
...especially about this season.
there are all these moments...

897
00:42:31.174 --> 00:42:33.301
...where Jimmy. and Chuck too. use...

898
00:42:33.468 --> 00:42:36.679
...sincere emotions in an insincere way.

899
00:42:36.846 --> 00:42:38.306
-Yeah. Good point.
-Especially...

900
00:42:38.473 --> 00:42:41.392
This scene and especially
episode seven that you have...

901
00:42:41.559 --> 00:42:43.811
...with the insurance...
The insurance lady.

902
00:42:43.978 --> 00:42:45.646
There's just...

903
00:42:46.355 --> 00:42:49.317
You can't quite see
what's real and what's not.

904
00:42:49.484 --> 00:42:51.152
-Right.
-It's fascinating.

905
00:42:51.319 --> 00:42:53.988
But on this scene. Bob.
we actually did two versions.

906
00:42:54.155 --> 00:42:56.365
You did one
where you did play it very sincere.

907
00:42:56.532 --> 00:43:00.078
And then we did one take
where we played more with seeing.

908
00:43:00.244 --> 00:43:02.181
-Oh. I don't even remember that.
-That you could see the scheme?

909
00:43:02.205 --> 00:43:04.040
Yeah. yeah.

910
00:43:04.207 --> 00:43:07.543
Something else I think...
Coming up here that I like...

911
00:43:07.710 --> 00:43:10.064
...that's happening with the character
as we've gone on with it...

912
00:43:10.088 --> 00:43:13.341
...is that it's like Jimmy steals things
from everywhere.

913
00:43:13.508 --> 00:43:14.675
He steals costuming.

914
00:43:14.842 --> 00:43:18.262
He steals lines from people and then
says them in a different context.

915
00:43:18.429 --> 00:43:22.308
When he tells her to listen to her heart.
that's what Howard told him in the pilot.

916
00:43:22.475 --> 00:43:25.186
-Yes.
-So he takes these little things...

917
00:43:25.353 --> 00:43:28.606
...and then re-twists them
and makes them his own.

918
00:43:28.940 --> 00:43:31.442
-He's like a magpie.
-He is.

919
00:43:31.609 --> 00:43:33.778
This is it.

920
00:43:36.197 --> 00:43:38.116
-Fake thinking.
-Fake thinking.

921
00:43:38.282 --> 00:43:39.325
It's great.

922
00:43:39.492 --> 00:43:42.245
-The layers there are pretty impressive.
-Oh. my God.

923
00:43:43.162 --> 00:43:45.832
And it looked like
you're still holding a cat prize.

924
00:43:45.998 --> 00:43:47.416
-I am.
-That's amazing.

925
00:43:49.377 --> 00:43:51.879
-Oh. the binders. Oh. those binders.
-Oh. the binders.

926
00:43:52.588 --> 00:43:54.590
This was complicated.
just to figure out how...

927
00:43:54.757 --> 00:43:56.968
...all of this laid out in the room.

928
00:43:57.135 --> 00:43:58.570
And there were so many moving parts.
and it had to just...

929
00:43:58.594 --> 00:44:00.555
And realistically... And the timing.

930
00:44:00.721 --> 00:44:02.201
-Yeah.
-And the resets. It was just...

931
00:44:02.306 --> 00:44:05.518
Because we do have such lovely fans
that will freeze-frame a scene.

932
00:44:05.685 --> 00:44:09.397
Tina Parker and I were over there
trying to figure out...

933
00:44:09.564 --> 00:44:12.650
...exactly which...
I tell her something's missing.

934
00:44:12.817 --> 00:44:15.653
Which I really think she should
probably be fired for. but it's fine.

935
00:44:15.820 --> 00:44:17.530
Well. she's getting coffee. so...

936
00:44:17.697 --> 00:44:19.157
Not a problem.

937
00:44:19.323 --> 00:44:22.618
Hey. who's ready
to have her life changed?

938
00:44:22.785 --> 00:44:24.787
A little Zafiro Añejo.

939
00:44:24.954 --> 00:44:27.874
Yes. soon available
at a liquor store near you.

940
00:44:28.207 --> 00:44:31.878
That's how strong that shit is.
It changes your life.

941
00:44:32.044 --> 00:44:34.630
-It's true.
-Change the direction of your life.

942
00:44:34.797 --> 00:44:36.215
Drink our tequila.

943
00:44:37.508 --> 00:44:39.260
We can't promise it'll go better.

944
00:44:39.886 --> 00:44:41.637
-Just different.
-But it'll change.

945
00:44:42.180 --> 00:44:44.515
-It'll be different.
-One way or another.

946
00:44:44.682 --> 00:44:46.684
Don't you have a bottle of that. Melissa?

947
00:44:46.851 --> 00:44:48.269
I... Oh. always. yes.

948
00:44:48.436 --> 00:44:51.606
-No. like. the actual... The original?
-Yeah. I do.

949
00:44:51.772 --> 00:44:53.649
It's kept in a vault.

950
00:44:53.816 --> 00:44:56.569
It's a precious item.

951
00:44:58.779 --> 00:45:01.157
Didn't George Clooney just sell
his tequila company?

952
00:45:01.324 --> 00:45:04.035
-Yes.
-He did. For like a billion dollars.

953
00:45:04.202 --> 00:45:05.922
-Don't you think that's on our minds?
-What?

954
00:45:05.953 --> 00:45:07.496
Why is that...? What?

955
00:45:07.663 --> 00:45:09.040
It's delicious.

956
00:45:09.207 --> 00:45:10.833
What?

957
00:45:11.167 --> 00:45:13.044
That's insane.

958
00:45:14.462 --> 00:45:18.633
I love how Kim handles him here.
She's such an adult.

959
00:45:21.385 --> 00:45:24.972
But her ponytail is split.
so nothing good can happen.

960
00:45:25.389 --> 00:45:26.989
That was a very conscious decision by...

961
00:45:27.141 --> 00:45:30.186
Yes. it's always conscious
if it involves my ponytail.

962
00:45:30.353 --> 00:45:31.562
Yeah.

963
00:45:32.104 --> 00:45:33.814
What does the ponytail tell us?

964
00:45:33.981 --> 00:45:35.566
It's unraveling a bit.

965
00:45:35.733 --> 00:45:37.526
-Yeah.
-Get it?

966
00:45:39.779 --> 00:45:41.781
Bob. you and I had
a good time playing this.

967
00:45:41.948 --> 00:45:44.909
Like. on what level is she taking him in
and spurning him?

968
00:45:45.076 --> 00:45:47.828
Because. again...
Because of the deftness of writing...

969
00:45:47.995 --> 00:45:50.081
...both people have a point.

970
00:45:50.248 --> 00:45:53.042
He's like. "Give me five minutes."
She's like. "I'm freaking working.

971
00:45:53.209 --> 00:45:56.796
Why don't you help with that? Why don't
you carry these binders. a-hole?"

972
00:45:58.089 --> 00:46:00.841
It's the biggest moment of his life.

973
00:46:01.842 --> 00:46:03.678
He thinks he solved all their problems.

974
00:46:03.844 --> 00:46:06.055
Kim definitely thinks
there's something weird...

975
00:46:06.222 --> 00:46:08.099
-...about him saying they settled.
-Yes.

976
00:46:08.266 --> 00:46:09.392
And so...

977
00:46:09.558 --> 00:46:14.063
What I like about how you played it
is it's a fight that you just had...

978
00:46:14.230 --> 00:46:17.066
...but it's so compact that it doesn't...

979
00:46:17.233 --> 00:46:20.194
It's not yelling and screaming
at one another. but just...

980
00:46:20.361 --> 00:46:23.030
...around the edges. fraying.
Like the ponytail.

981
00:46:23.197 --> 00:46:25.449
It's probably the worst fight
we've ever seen them have.

982
00:46:25.616 --> 00:46:26.909
Yeah.

983
00:46:30.496 --> 00:46:31.539
This is a very...

984
00:46:31.706 --> 00:46:34.101
Am I on the flatbed here
or am I driving? Because we did both.

985
00:46:34.125 --> 00:46:35.710
-Flatbed.
-Flatbed.

986
00:46:36.210 --> 00:46:38.796
Very interesting choice...

987
00:46:39.130 --> 00:46:41.132
...and I think effective.

988
00:46:41.299 --> 00:46:43.884
You guys are happy with this.
Did you talk about it a lot?

989
00:46:44.051 --> 00:46:47.430
Look at Cheri Montesanto's make-up.
the subtle. like. fatigue.

990
00:46:47.596 --> 00:46:49.640
-Yeah.
-But. yes. talk about the direction...

991
00:46:49.807 --> 00:46:51.567
...and choices here.
You guys did a good job.

992
00:46:51.642 --> 00:46:53.394
You know. I can't take credit. sadly.

993
00:46:53.561 --> 00:46:56.314
It was a... You know. Peter.
you came up with this idea...

994
00:46:56.480 --> 00:46:59.817
...of never. ever seeing the crash
and just going for the match cut.

995
00:46:59.984 --> 00:47:02.737
This is something that.
well. in the writers' room. we...

996
00:47:02.903 --> 00:47:06.574
We had talked about
how to show a crash.

997
00:47:06.741 --> 00:47:09.910
And we don't like to put everything
into the director's lap.

998
00:47:10.077 --> 00:47:13.080
But we wanted to do it
differently and subjectively.

999
00:47:13.247 --> 00:47:18.085
Also. you could feel something
was gonna happen. which is so weird.

1000
00:47:18.252 --> 00:47:21.422
Just a testament to the whole show
and the rhythm of the show and...

1001
00:47:21.589 --> 00:47:24.675
...the notion of that silence
made you go. "Something bad..."

1002
00:47:24.842 --> 00:47:26.260
Yeah. yeah.

1003
00:47:26.427 --> 00:47:27.845
Talk about Cheri's work.

1004
00:47:28.012 --> 00:47:29.388
-Yeah.
-Yeah.

1005
00:47:29.555 --> 00:47:32.266
She researched the hell out of that...
What kind of burns...

1006
00:47:32.433 --> 00:47:34.352
...you get from airbags.

1007
00:47:34.518 --> 00:47:38.981
-And this shot is just spectacular.
-It's so beautiful.

1008
00:47:39.148 --> 00:47:43.861
And this car is really trashed.
you guys. for people listening.

1009
00:47:44.195 --> 00:47:46.322
-Into a fake boulder. correct?
-Yes.

1010
00:47:46.489 --> 00:47:49.200
But on the real side of the road.
being held on by a cable.

1011
00:47:49.367 --> 00:47:52.578
And the angle is quite. quite extreme.

1012
00:47:52.745 --> 00:47:54.955
Yeah. this was...

1013
00:47:55.122 --> 00:47:57.500
This was on the edge of being...

1014
00:47:57.666 --> 00:48:00.252
It's done very safely.
but it could've been dangerous...

1015
00:48:00.419 --> 00:48:02.671
...if it wasn't done so professionally.

1016
00:48:02.838 --> 00:48:04.006
But it was days of prep.

1017
00:48:04.173 --> 00:48:07.468
It was days of wrecking. scouting and...

1018
00:48:07.635 --> 00:48:11.597
And Joe. our Special Effects.
is in that back seat. crouched down.

1019
00:48:11.764 --> 00:48:14.350
Helping the papers get out
of the trunk with the breeze.

1020
00:48:14.517 --> 00:48:16.435
There's a fan offside.

1021
00:48:16.602 --> 00:48:20.022
That's actually a road Walter White
drove down many a time...

1022
00:48:20.189 --> 00:48:23.192
-...way back when.
-A whole two miles from our stages.

1023
00:48:23.359 --> 00:48:24.819
-That's right.
-Yes. indeed.

1024
00:48:24.985 --> 00:48:27.071
What a... That was a hell of an episode.

1025
00:48:27.238 --> 00:48:28.598
-It went fast.
-Such a big episode.

1026
00:48:28.739 --> 00:48:30.825
-Oh. yeah.
-What's gonna happen?

1027
00:48:30.991 --> 00:48:33.869
-What's gonna happen?
-What happens in episode 10?

1028
00:48:34.036 --> 00:48:35.579
-Nobody knows.
-Nobody knows.

1029
00:48:35.746 --> 00:48:37.581
-Can't be told.
-That was great.

1030
00:48:38.499 --> 00:48:40.418
-Great job. Minkie and Gordon.
-Great job.

1031
00:48:40.584 --> 00:48:42.128
Thank you. Minkie.

1032
00:48:42.628 --> 00:48:44.672
Yes. Excellent.

1033
00:48:44.839 --> 00:48:46.590
Well done. all.

